answers.body_markdown:
If you want to execute multiple statements atomically, you need to use a transaction. A JDBC connection defaults to &#39;auto-commit&#39; mode, which means each statement is executed in its own transaction. So you first need to disable auto-commit mode, using [`Connection.setAutoCommit(false)`][1].

With auto-commit mode disabled, executed statements will be executed in the current transaction, if there is no current transaction, one will be started. This transaction can then either be committed using [`Connection.commit()`][2] or rolled back using [`Connection.rollback()`][3].

You will need to do something like:

```java
try (Connection connection = DriverManager.getConnection(...)) {
    connection.setAutoCommit(false);
    try (Statement stmt = connection.createStatement()) {
        stmt.executeUpdate(&lt;your first update&gt;);
        stmt.executeUpdate(&lt;your second update&gt;);

        connection.commit();
    } catch (SQLException e) {
        connection.rollback();
        throw e;
    }
}
```

For more details, see the JDBC tutorial chapter [Using Transactions][4].

And please learn about prepared statements. Concatenating values into a query string is bad, because it can lead to SQL injection or weird errors if you forget to escape values. See also the JDBC tutorial chapter [Using Prepared Statements][5].

  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/sql/Connection.html#setAutoCommit-boolean-
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/sql/Connection.html#commit--
  [3]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/sql/Connection.html#rollback--
  [4]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/jdbc/basics/transactions.html
  [5]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/jdbc/basics/prepared.html

